  "doc_id": "18455",
  "text": "However, some experts [CITATION_1] warn that clusters may also inhibit innovation (negative externalities, excessive competition, and knowledge leakage). Nonetheless, many empirical studies reveal a rather positive relationship between clusters and innovation. In an article, [CITATION_2] performed a meta-analysis of empirical studies on the relationships between clusters and innovations since the 1980s. The results show that clusters have a positive effect on innovation. At the same time, it must be noted that this positive relationship is not automatic and may be limited to a certain number of industries, certain development phases, certain locations, and certain specific conditions [CITATION_3] . The effect of the various industries on innovation performance was addressed by Žižka et al. (2016) . The research assessed the performance of Czech innovative enterprises in 15 different industries using a two-stage DEA method. In the first stage, they measured the enterprises' ability to use available resources to generate the results of technical creative activities and subsequently the ability to commercialise the results. They came to the conclusion that innovation performance depends on the industry. In both components, it was found that the automotive industry had the largest proportion of successful firms, while the chemical industry had the smallest proportion. The research presented in this paper attempts to reveal whether cluster organisations that are set up to boost innovation have any effect on the innovation performance of enterprises.",
